         <abstract>
            <p>Two alternative methodologies for measuring the effects of changes in credit policies are shown to have the same theoretical basis and to yield equivalent results. The simpler formulation is used to convey the basic patterns of analysis used in the measurement of the net present value of changes in credit policy.</p>
         </abstract>
